Trucks and Willys MB jeeps which will carry men and supplies of the U.S. 32nd Field Artillery Regiment / 1st Infantry Division "The Big Red One" to the front lines of the invasion in Normandy on D-Day are being loaded onto an American Landing Craft, Castletown Road Slipway, Portland, Dorset (England), June 5th, 1944. The Divisional HQ jeep at right (with Divisional HQ tactical insignia in the bumper: black star on dark yellow circle; 1-X: indication of the Division Headquarters; Star in center bumper; HQ-19: 19th vehicle of the Division Headquarters; and Barcode with five-digit number of the DivHQ) has an 15'x15' vehicle camouflage net (this type of net with interwoven twine came in different sizes) above the white star on a yellow background marking. The yellowy green (or greeny yellow) background between star and circle was a kind of gas detecting paint that was supposed to change colour during a chemical attack. Presumably these jeeps are an example of the stuff. Might also be worth noting that a yellow or white star in black and white photos would show up the same tone. Closer analysis of even quite familiar black and white pictures recently seems to be turning up even camo schemes that have been almost lost in the monochrome process. In the dust and confusion of the battles in the North Africa previously, the US star could be mistaken for a German Cross at long range (greater then 1000 yards). Tankers and armored units began painting out the stars to avoid becoming a casualty of ‘friendly fire’. The addition of the circle around the star helped to resolve this problem, though some of the more experienced units (like the 2nd Armored) stayed with the painted out stars until the Normandy landings. There they painted the vehicle number on the sides of the turret in yellow. This was painted out by D-Day + 14. After Normandy several armored divisions were sent into Europe but kept their stateside markings, except the bar, and that is why one sees so many variations in pictures.

Castle Clinton, at the southern tip of Manhattan Island in Battery Park, was built in 1808 as part of a buildup of defenses in the city during the escalation of hostility between the United States and Britain prior to the War of 1812. It never saw any action in battle, however, and was decommissioned by the Army in 1821 and deeded to the city in 1823. The following year, it reopened as "Castle Garden," a restaurant and entertainment hall. It featured operas, concerts, and other spectacles, including famously the American debut of the Swedish singer Jenny Lind (basically the Beyoncé of the 1850s). In 1855, Castle Garden was repurposed to serve at New York's first immigrant processing depot. Prior to this, newly arrived migrants would simply disembark at Manhattan's piers and, more often than not, vanish into the throngs of the bustling city to make their fortunes. Castle Garden would go on to process more than 7 million new immigrants from 1855 until the opening of Ellis Island in 1890, roughly 2/3 of all new arrivals to America during that period. (Fun fact: one of those migrants was a certain Friedrich Trumpf, grandfather of our current president.) The building was again repurposed in 1896, when it reopened as the New York City Aquarium. The aquarium was one of the city's top attractions, with hundreds of thousands of visitors each year until its closure in 1941. That year, city planner Robert Moses sought to move the aquarium to the Bronx Zoo, demolish Castle Clinton, and build a bridge through Battery Park connecting Manhattan to Brooklyn. He was defeated on all 3 counts by a mix of public outcry and mayoral obstruction. Moses was forced to build a tunnel instead of a bridge, and Castle Clinton was declared a National Monument, saving it from demolition. In a fury, Moses banished the aquarium to Coney Island, far from most of the city's residents in what was then a rapidly decaying area. Castle Clinton, meanwhile, was restored to its 1808 appearance, its many additions and alterations stripped away. Today, it is a ticket counter and point of departure for tourists visiting the Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island.

Déjà vu 🇫🇷/🇩🇪
_
Germany's attack against the Western Allies in France on May 10, 1940 mirrored the initial success of the Schlieffen Plan of 1914. The Germans plowed their way through neutral Belgium and the Netherlands, and crashed into France through the Ardennes with three Panzer corps spearheading their attack - just like the previous generation of Germans had done almost 26 years before (just without the armor). In the ensuing chaos of early May 1940, the Germans managed to surrounded and isolate about nearly half a million Allied troops along the northern French coast in a pocket. For those in the German trap, there was no way out - the English Channel was at their backs.

Almost immediately a plan was devised by the commander of the British Expeditionary Force, Field Marshall John Vereker, 6th Viscount Gort, to carry out an organized withdrawal to the only ample port city around: Dunkirk. From there the stranded French and British troops would be evacuated and shipped to England.

When Disneyland opened in 1955, there were actually two completely different trains that circled the park. The "Frontier Train" was a series of cattle cars that circled the park with only one stop, Frontierland. Surprisingly, it had few seats, as guests would be mainly standing. The train was short lived and only lasted for about a year..
